  <title>Getting Started</title>

  <p>Welcome to <app>Audio Recorder</app>! This guide will help you get started 
  with recording and managing audio tracks.</p>

  <section id="requirements">
    <title>Requirements</title>
    <list>
      <item><p>GNOME desktop environment (or GTK4/libadwaita compatible desktop)</p></item>
      <item><p>PipeWire audio system with <cmd>pw-record</cmd> and <cmd>pw-play</cmd></p></item>
      <item><p>GStreamer 1.0 for playback</p></item>
    </list>
  </section>

  <section id="first-recording">
    <title>Your First Recording</title>
    <steps>
      <item><p>Launch <app>Audio Recorder</app>. A new project with one empty track is created automatically.</p></item>
      <item><p>Click the <gui style="button">Record</gui> button (red circle) on the track.</p></item>
      <item><p>Speak or play your audio.</p></item>
      <item><p>Click the <gui style="button">Stop</gui> button to finish recording.</p></item>
      <item><p>Click the <gui style="button">Play</gui> button to listen to your recording.</p></item>
    </steps>
  </section>

  <section id="saving">
    <title>Saving Your Work</title>
    <p>To save your project:</p>
    <steps>
      <item><p>Press <keyseq><key>Ctrl</key><key>S</key></keyseq> or select 
      <guiseq><gui>Menu</gui><gui>Save Project</gui></guiseq>.</p></item>
      <item><p>Choose a location and name for your project folder.</p></item>
      <item><p>Your project and all recordings are saved together.</p></item>
    </steps>
    <note style="tip">
      <p>The application will prompt you to save unsaved work when closing.</p>
    </note>
  </section>

